I"<p>I am an <em>Environmental Data Scientist</em> at the British Antarctic Survey (<a href="http://www.bas.ac.uk">BAS</a>) and a <em>Senior Research Fellow</em> at the <a href="https://www.turing.ac.uk/">Alan Turing Institute</a>. My research involves the application of AI and machine learning techniques on vast and various datasets, including the output from global climate models and weather stations.  The primary aims of my work is to identify and understand the key mechanisms that drive year-to-year climate variability over vulnerable regions, the changes in frequency and strength of extreme weather events, and to reduce uncertainties in future climate predictions to help drive environmental policy.</p>

<p>I am the <strong>Head</strong> of the <a href="http://www.bas.ac.uk/ai"><em>BAS AI Lab</em></a>, and a <strong>Co-Director</strong> of the Centre for Doctoral Training (CDT) in the <em>Application of AI for the study of Environmental Risks</em> (<a href="https://ai4er-cdt.esc.cam.ac.uk/"><em>AI4ER</em></a>) which is jointly led with the University of Cambridge.</p>

